{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17569524","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17569524"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:24+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:28:24+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22265"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22265","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22265"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0.19,0.12,0.37,0.22]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15230"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109450"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15230","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15230"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22265"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91815"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1783"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"12920"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"40239"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40241"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40887"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/109450"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 53-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-month history of scaly, red patches. He denies any previous rashes prior to this. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are extensive well-demarcated, erythematous plaques with silvery scales covering approximately 30% of his body surface area, including his trunk, limbs and scalp (image). The lesions are moderately pruritic and interfering with his daily activities and sleep. No joint swelling or tenderness is noted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has tried topical calcipotriol and betamethasone combination for six weeks with minimal improvement and is looking for further management options.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management for this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Adalimumab injections","Oral acitretin","Topical tacrolimus","Narrowband UVB phototherapy","Oral methotrexate"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with severe plaque psoriasis that has not responded adequately to first-line topical therapy. The peak onset can be either 15\u201330 years and 50\u201360 years, and it has a genetic link. Using the Psoriasis Area and Severity Index (PASI) score based on the given the extensive body surface area involvement (approximately 30%) and the significant impact on the patient\u0027s quality of life, systemic therapy is now indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral acitretin\u003C/strong\u003E is an appropriate next step for this patient with severe psoriasis. It is a systemic retinoid that works by normalising keratinocyte differentiation and reducing inflammation. It is particularly effective for pustular and erythrodermic variants of psoriasis but can also be effective for extensive plaque psoriasis. The typical starting dose is 10-25 mg daily, which can be adjusted based on response and tolerability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENarrowband UVB phototherapy\u003C/strong\u003E could be considered as an option, but given the extensive nature of the disease and its impact on the patient\u0027s quality of life, a systemic treatment would be more appropriate at this stage. Phototherapy also requires frequent clinic visits (2-3 times weekly), which may be impractical for many patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral methotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is another systemic treatment option for moderate to severe psoriasis. While it is effective and commonly used, acitretin may be preferred initially in patients without comorbidities due to its more favorable long-term safety profile, particularly regarding liver toxicity. Methotrexate would be a reasonable alternative if acitretin is contraindicated or not tolerated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical tacrolimus\u003C/strong\u003E is sometimes used for psoriasis in sensitive areas like the face or genitals. However, it\u0027s not typically more effective than the calcipotriol and betamethasone combination that the patient has already tried, and would be inadequate for such extensive disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdalimumab\u003C/strong\u003E is a TNF-alpha inhibitor biologic therapy typically reserved for severe psoriasis that hasn\u0027t responded to conventional systemic treatments like acitretin or methotrexate. While effective, biologics are generally considered third-line therapy due to cost and potential side effects. They would be considered if the patient fails to respond to conventional systemic therapies.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that acitretin is teratogenic and should not be used in women of childbearing potential unless effective contraception is ensured. Common side effects include mucocutaneous dryness, hair loss, and hyperlipidemia. Regular monitoring of lipids and liver function is required due to the higher risk of cardiovascular events, and patient\u0027s screened for symptoms of psoriatic arthritis and mental health conditions. Lastly, the patient should also be counseled about sun protection as acitretin can increase photosensitivity.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Oral acitretin is effective for severe plaque psoriasis when topical treatments have failed.","Systemic treatments are indicated for moderate to severe psoriasis that has not responded to topical therapy.","Treatment selection for psoriasis depends on disease severity, distribution, and previous treatment response."],"references":["Jones C, Gupta M, Uddin S, Oakley A, Coulson I. Psoriasis. In: DermnetNZ. 2023. Available in: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/psoriasis","Zhang P, Wu M. A Clinical review of phototherapy for psoriasis. Lasers Medical Science. 2018; 33 (1): 173- 180.  Available in: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC5756569/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22265"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20786"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20786","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20786"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jI9tk2IqhI024vhfZp06lCajvKU0RP.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/jI9tk2IqhI024vhfZp06lCajvKU0RP.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":768,"height":1024}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"91815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/91815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-21T13:35:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-21T13:36:52+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15230"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"109450"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"t